lection":null,"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2020-04-17T15:04:10.664Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"The reason why some people don't wash their hands","headlineShort":"Why some people don’t wash their hands","image":["p089spnf"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e9821532567d5de226b3500"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fhealth"],"summaryLong":"There are millions of non-hand-washers hiding among us. Why won’t they adopt this simple hygiene habit – and how can we change their minds?","summaryShort":"They know who they are – but what’s driving them?","tag":["tag\u002Fcovid-19"],"creationDateTime":"2020-04-20T02:45:44.91871Z","entity":"article","guid":"93376081-8e57-407e-a8ea-0b0fe7293229","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200417-the-hidden-reasons-some-people-dont-wash-their-hands","modifiedDateTime":"2020-04-20T13:02:57.121015Z","project":"future","slug":"20200417-the-hidden-reasons-some-people-dont-wash-their-hands","cacheLastUpdated":1587442683496},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you","_id":"5e9820ad2567d5de2265980f","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fzaria-gorvett"],"bodyIntro":"Forget kombucha and trendy vitamin supplements – they are nothing more than magic potions for the modern age.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Spanish Influenza &ndash; what it is and how it should be treated,&rdquo; read the reassuringly factual headline to an \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fexhibits.lib.unc.edu\u002Fexhibits\u002Fshow\u002Fgoing-viral\u002Fitem\u002F5576\"\u003Eadvert for Vick&rsquo;s VapoRub back in 1918\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The text beneath included nuggets of wisdom such as &ldquo;stay quiet&rdquo; and &ldquo;take a laxative&rdquo;. Oh, and to apply their ointment liberally, of course.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe 1918 flu pandemic was \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20181016-the-flu-that-transformed-the-20th-century\"\u003Ethe most lethal in recorded history\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, infecting up to 500 million people (a quarter of the world&rsquo;s population at the time) and killing tens of millions worldwide.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut with crisis comes opportunity, and the &ndash; sometimes literal &ndash; snake oil salesmen were out in force. Vick&rsquo;s VapoRub had stiff competition from a panoply of crackpot remedies, including \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.eiu.edu\u002Fhistoria\u002F2010Shidler.pdf\"\u003EMiller&rsquo;s Antiseptic Snake Oil\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, Dr Bell&rsquo;s Pine Tar Honey, Schenck&rsquo;s Mandrake Pills, Dr Jones&rsquo;s Liniment, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.laphamsquarterly.org\u002Froundtable\u002Feat-more-onions\"\u003EHill&rsquo;s Cascara Quinine Bromide\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and A. Wulfing &amp; Co&rsquo;s famous mint lozenges. Their adverts made regular appearances in the newspapers, where they starred alongside increasingly alarming headlines.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFast-forward to 2020, and not much has changed. Though the Covid-19 pandemic is separated from the Spanish flu by over a century of scientific discoveries, there are still plenty of questionable medicinal concoctions and folk remedies floating around. This time, the theme is &ldquo;boosting&rdquo; the immune system.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOf the rumours currently circulating on social media, one of the more bizarre is the idea that you can raise your white blood cell count by masturbating more. And as always, nutritional advice abounds. This time, we&rsquo;re being encouraged to seek out foods rich in antioxidants and vitamin C (back in 1918, the public were told to eat more onions), while pseudoscientists are peddling trendy products such as \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nutraingredients.com\u002FArticle\u002F2020\u002F03\u002F23\u002FMicrobiome-maintenance-Good-gut-health-could-tackle-COVID-19\"\u003Ekombucha\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.biogaia.com\u002Fother-news\u002Fcovid-19-outbreak-and-probiotics-facts\u002F\"\u003Eprobiotics\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cul\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20200330-coronavirus-are-children-immune-to-covid-19\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EWhy children are not immune to Covid-19\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20200327-can-you-kill-coronavirus-with-uv-light\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ECan you kill coronavirus with UV light? \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20200406-why-smart-people-believe-coronavirus-myths\" target=\"_blank\"\u003EWhy smart people believe coronavirus myths\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAccording to one source, cayenne pepper and green tea can provide better protection against Covid-19\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.mirror.co.uk\u002Flifestyle\u002Fhealth\u002F7-ways-improve-your-immune-21580462\"\u003E than face masks\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; a bold and highly dubious claim, considering that some face masks reduce your risk of contracting respiratory viruses by a factor of five. (\u003Cem\u003ERead more about \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20200406-are-there-benefits-to-eating-turmeric-and-other-spices\"\u003Ewhat evidence exists for the idea that spices can affect your health\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and how \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20200403-coronavirus-will-hot-drinks-protect-you-from-covid-19\"\u003Ehot drinks will not protect you from Covid-19\u003C\u002Fa\u003E).\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThere&rsquo;s no such thing as boosted immunity\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EUnfortunately, the idea that pills, trendy superfoods or wellness habits can provide a shortcut to a healthy immune system is a myth. In fact, the concept of &ldquo;boosting&rdquo; your immune system doesn&rsquo;t hold any scientific meaning whatsoever.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;There are three different components to immunity,&rdquo; says Akiko Iwasaki, an immunologist at Yale University. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s things like skin, the airways and the mucus membranes that are there to begin with, and they provide a barrier to infection. But once the virus gets past these defences, then you have to induce the &lsquo;innate&rsquo; immune response.&rdquo; This consists of chemicals and cells which can rapidly raise the alert and begin fighting off any intruder.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"infographic","imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0890nv4"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"An Italian advert for a remedy during the 1918 flu pandemic (Credit: Getty Images)","imageCaption":"The 1918 flu pandemic was an opportunity for snake oil salesmen to market their useless - and sometimes harmful - products (Credit: Getty Images)","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;When that is not enough, then we kick in the adaptive immune system,&rdquo; she says. This involves cells and proteins &ndash; antibodies &ndash; which take a few days or weeks to emerge. Importantly, the adaptive immune system can only target particular pathogens. &ldquo;So, for example, a T-cell specific to Covid-19 will not respond to influenza or bacterial pathogens.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EMost infections will trigger adaptive immunity eventually. But there's another way to get it going, and that's vaccination: exposing the body to live or dead microbes, or parts of them, can help the body to identify the real deal when it comes along.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe concept of &ldquo;boosting&rdquo; a person&rsquo;s immune system would, presumably, involve making these responses more active, or stronger.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn actuality, you wouldn&rsquo;t want to do this.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETake the symptoms of a cold &ndash; body aches, a fever, brain fog, copious amounts of snot and phlegm. Most of these problems aren&rsquo;t actually caused by the virus itself. Instead, they&rsquo;re triggered by your own body, on purpose: they&rsquo;re part of the innate immune response.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Many “immunity-boosting” products claim to reduce inflammation","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the mucus helps to flush out the pathogen, the fever helps to make your body an uncomfortably hot environment in which it&rsquo;s harder for it to replicate, and the aches and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencemag.org\u002Fnews\u002F2016\u002F04\u002Fhere-s-why-you-feel-so-crummy-when-you-re-sick\"\u003Egeneral malaise\u003C\u002Fa\u003E are by-products of the inflammatory chemicals that course through your veins, telling immune cells what to do and where to go. (These symptoms also help signal to your brain that it&rsquo;s time to slow down and let your body recover).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe mucus and chemical signals are part of inflammation, which is \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3282411\u002F\"\u003Ethe bedrock of a healthy immune response\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. But the process is exhausting, so you wouldn&rsquo;t want to have it turned up to 11 all the time. And most viruses, including Covid-19, will trigger it anyway. If kombucha, green tea or any of the various &ldquo;immune-boosting&rdquo; concoctions on the market really had any impact, they wouldn&rsquo;t give you a healthful glow: they&rsquo;d give you a runny nose.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIronically, many &ldquo;immunity-boosting&rdquo; products claim to reduce inflammation.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0890mvk"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"Empty vitamin shelves in a supermarket (Credit: Reuters)","imageCaption":"There is no evidence that vitamin supplements will protect you from infections, unless you are deficient (Credit: Reuters)","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EMaking the other aspect of immunity &ndash; the adaptive immune system &ndash; generally more active could also be extremely unpleasant. For example, allergies occur when overzealous immune cells learn to treat innocuous foreign bodies, such as pollen, as though they are harmful. Each time they find the offending substance, they switch on the innate immune response too &ndash; cue lots of sneezing, itchy eyes and general fatigue. Again, this is probably not what the people championing these remedies have in mind.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut let&rsquo;s give those saying you can &ldquo;boost&rdquo; your immune system the benefit of the doubt and assume they mean that certain products can improve the immune response in a useful way &ndash; rather than literally &ldquo;boost&rdquo; it.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The problem is that many of these claims have no grounding in evidence,&rdquo; Iwasaki says. So what are they based on &ndash; and is there anything that can help?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIf you&rsquo;re healthy, forget supplements &ndash; except vitamin D\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EMany multivitamins claim to provide &ldquo;immune support&rdquo; or to help &ldquo;maintain healthy immune function&rdquo;. But as BBC Future reported in 2016, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20161208-why-vitamin-supplements-could-kill-you\"\u003Evitamin supplements generally don&rsquo;t work\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in already healthy people &ndash; and some may even be harmful.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETake vitamin C. The health effects of this antioxidant have been steeped in mythology ever since the two-time Nobel Prize winner Linus Pauling became obsessed with its ability to fight the common cold. After studying the vitamin for years, eventually he started taking 18,000 mg per day &ndash; around 300 times the current recommended daily amount.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Vitamin supplements aren’t beneficial to your immune system unless you are deficient","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EHowever, there is little evidence to support vitamin C&rsquo;s mighty reputation for helping us to fight off colds and other respiratory infections. A \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cochrane.org\u002FCD000980\u002FARI_vitamin-c-for-preventing-and-treating-the-common-cold\"\u003E2013 review\u003C\u002Fa\u003E by Cochrane &ndash; an organisation renowned for its unbiased research &ndash; found that in adults &ldquo;trials of high doses of vitamin C administered therapeutically, starting after the onset of symptoms, showed no consistent effect on the duration or severity of common cold symptoms&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn fact, many experts consider the vitamin C market \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.vox.com\u002F2015\u002F1\u002F15\u002F7547741\u002Fvitamin-c-myth-pauling\"\u003Eto be a bit of a racket\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, as most people in the developed world get enough from their diets already. Though scurvy is thought to have killed two million sailors and pirates between the 15th and 18th Centuries, the numbers now are far lower. For example, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Ftheconversation.com\u002Fscurvy-is-it-really-making-a-comeback-in-the-uk-124841\"\u003Ejust 128 people in England\u003C\u002Fa\u003E were hospitalised with the disease between 2016 and 2017. On the other hand, high doses of this vitamin can \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.healthline.com\u002Fnutrition\u002Fside-effects-of-too-much-vitamin-c\"\u003Elead to kidney stones\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Vitamin supplements aren&rsquo;t beneficial to your immune system unless you are deficient,&rdquo; says Iwasaki.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0890mhq"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"An assortment of vegetables in a wooden crate (Credit: Getty Images)","imageCaption":"Brightly coloured fruits and vegetables tend to contain the most antioxidants, because the compounds are often pigmented (Credit: Getty Images)","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the developed world, most people get enough vitamins from their diets (unless they are restricted &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20200127-how-a-vegan-diet-could-affect-your-intelligence\"\u003Evegans, for example, are more likely to have certain deficiencies\u003C\u002Fa\u003E). However, there is one exception &ndash; vitamin D. Iwasaki explains that taking this supplement wouldn&rsquo;t be a bad idea.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESeveral studies have linked low vitamin D levels to a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F19237723\"\u003Ehigher risk of respiratory infections\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and more severe symptoms when they develop. They&rsquo;ve also been \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.sciencedaily.com\u002Freleases\u002F2019\u002F04\u002F190417111440.htm\"\u003Eimplicated in the development of autoimmune diseases\u003C\u002Fa\u003E such as multiple sclerosis.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn fact, many immune cells can actively recognise vitamin D, and it&rsquo;s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3166406\u002F\"\u003Ethought to play an important role in both the innate and acquired immune response\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; though exactly how remains a mystery.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut crucially &ndash; and unusually &ndash; vitamin D deficiencies are endemic in many countries, even wealthy ones. As of 2012, it was estimated that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F22629085\"\u003Eabout a billion people worldwide\u003C\u002Fa\u003E weren&rsquo;t getting enough. And with more and more people urged to stay indoors, it&rsquo;s easy to see how even less sunlight exposure could lead to more deficiencies. \u003Cem\u003E(Read more about \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20181010-do-vitamin-d-supplements-work\"\u003Ewho needs to take vitamin D and why\u003C\u002Fa\u003E).\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo, masturbation won&rsquo;t help either \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHistorically, this form of sexual activity was held in deep suspicion by Western medicine. After an 18th Century doctor claimed that the loss of one ounce of semen (28 millilitres) had the same effect on the body as losing 40 ounces (1.18 litres) of blood, masturbation was blamed for all kinds of health problems for hundreds of years, from blindness to neurosis.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENow the tables have turned, and recent research has shown that it can come with some surprising health benefits. In men, for example, it&rsquo;s thought to help keep sperm healthy and may \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.europeanurology.com\u002Farticle\u002FS0302-2838%2816%2900377-8\u002Ffulltext\"\u003Ereduce a person&rsquo;s risk of developing prostate cancer\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The question of whether antioxidants can help is slightly more complicated","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAlas, any claims that masturbation can improve your immunity or protect you from Covid-19 are overblown. It&rsquo;s true that one study found that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F15316239\"\u003Emen had higher white blood cell counts\u003C\u002Fa\u003E when they were sexually aroused, and during orgasm. However, there is no evidence that this translates into protection from infections.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThere is one way that the practice might protect you &ndash; by keeping away from other people. On Twitter, the&nbsp;New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene recently reminded their followers that, in the age of Covid-19, &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FnycHealthy\u002Fstatus\u002F1242462479134982145?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1242462479134982145&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Ftwitter.com%2FnycHealthy%2Fstatus%2F1242462479134982145\"\u003Eyou are your safest sex partner\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThere&rsquo;s no need to stock up on antioxidant pills\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe question of whether antioxidants can help is slightly more complicated.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs part of the inflammatory response, white blood cells release toxic oxygen compounds. These are something of a double-edged sword. On the one hand, they can kill bacteria and viruses and stop them from being able to make more copies of themselves. On the other, they can damage healthy cells, leading to cancer and ageing &ndash; and wearing out the immune system.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETo stop this from happening, the body relies on antioxidants. These help to control those unruly oxygen compounds and keep our cells safe.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnd we get some of our reserves of these compounds from our diets. Brightly coloured fruits, vegetables and spices tend to contain the most, because antioxidants are often pigmented: they give carrots, blueberries, aubergines, red kale, turmeric, and strawberries their hues.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0890pks"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"A glass of kombucha, a type of fermented tea (Credit: Getty Images)","imageCaption":"Wellness experts like to promote kombucha as more than just a drink - but there's no evidence that it can treat or prevent any illnesses, including Covid-19 (Credit: Getty Images)","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThere&rsquo;s currently a trial in the works to test if giving \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fclinicaltrials.gov\u002Fct2\u002Fshow\u002FNCT04323228\"\u003Epeople with Covid-19 antioxidant supplements\u003C\u002Fa\u003E might help their recovery.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHowever, the trial is just one of hundreds looking into potential treatments for Covid-19. And despite decades of research, not a single placebo-controlled, peer-reviewed study on humans has ever shown that high doses of antioxidants can &ldquo;boost&rdquo; the immune system, or treat or prevent viral infections in humans.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProbiotics may help&hellip; or they may not\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIf you believe the wellness experts and homeopaths, kombucha is much more than a sweet, fizzy drink made from fermented tea. The internet is teeming with outrageous claims about the product, including that it can \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.salon.com\u002F2018\u002F05\u002F20\u002Fit-took-food-poisoning-losing-7500-and-an-intervention-to-make-me-realize-my-kombucha-problem\u002F\"\u003Etreat cancer\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and even \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ffood52.com\u002Fblog\u002F20366-queer-history-of-kombucha\"\u003EAids\u003C\u002Fa\u003E (it can&rsquo;t).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENow some websites are suggesting that it can \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nutraingredients.com\u002FArticle\u002F2020\u002F03\u002F23\u002FMicrobiome-maintenance-Good-gut-health-could-tackle-COVID-19\"\u003Ehelp to stop you getting Covid-19\u003C\u002Fa\u003E (and it probably can&rsquo;t).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ELike probiotics, kombucha contains live microorganisms. However, no studies have ever confirmed whether the drink has these in high enough concentrations to be considered one &ndash; and there is currently no evidence that kombucha specifically can treat or prevent any illnesses whatsoever.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe picture is less clear for probiotics in general.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"There is currently no evidence that any kind of probiotic can protect you from Covid-19","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne 2015 review found that probiotics &ndash; beneficial microorganisms which are concentrated in foods, drinks, or pills &ndash; significantly \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cochranelibrary.com\u002Fcdsr\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1002\u002F14651858.CD006895.pub3\u002Fabstract\"\u003Ereduced the number of&nbsp; upper respiratory tract infections\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that people got and made them less severe. They also slightly reduced the use of antibiotics and led to fewer school absences. The authors concluded that they might be better than placebo treatments, but pointed out that the quality of the available evidence was low.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E(You can find out more about \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20190121-what-we-do-and-dont-know-about-gut-health\"\u003Ewhat we do and don&rsquo;t know about gut health\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, as well as \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20190205-how-to-eat-your-way-to-a-healthy-gut\"\u003Ehow to eat your way to a healthy gut\u003C\u002Fa\u003E by checking out BBC Future&rsquo;s series on gut bacteria from last year. We found that it&rsquo;s true that gut bacteria are important &ndash; but that taking probiotics is unlikely to help you much, and that the best way forward is to simply eat a varied diet.)\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EImportantly, there is currently no evidence that any kind of probiotic can protect you from Covid-19.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESo what has been proven to work?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIwasaki says most of these myths are relatively innocuous &ndash; but the danger is that falling for them will give you a false sense of security. &ldquo;One thing I do warn against is when people feel like they're protected. They shouldn't feel empowered to go out there and, you know, start having parties,&rdquo; she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWellness products aside, there are some approaches you \u003Cem\u003Ecan \u003C\u002Fem\u003Etake to help support your immune system. They aren&rsquo;t especially sexy, and you won&rsquo;t see many wellness influencers selling them in a bottle. They are, however, proven to work &ndash; and they don&rsquo;t require shelling out your hard-earned cash: get enough sleep, exercise, eat a balanced diet, and try not to be stressed. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFailing that, there is one sure-fire way to improve your immunity to certain pathogens: vaccination.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin one million Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\u002F\"\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;or\u003Cstrong\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.instagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story,&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, called &ldquo;The Essential List&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Culture, Worklife, and Travel, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you-16"}],"collection":null,"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2020-04-09T22:00:00Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"Covid-19: Can 'boosting' your immune system protect you?","headlineShort":"Can you 'boost' your immune system?","image":["p0890nyn"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e9821532567d5de226b3500"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":[],"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fcovid-19"],"summaryLong":"Forget kombucha and trendy vitamin supplements – they are nothing more than magic potions for the modern age.","summaryShort":"No, kombucha won’t stop you getting Covid-19","tag":["tag\u002Fcovid-19","tag\u002Fhealth"],"creationDateTime":"2020-04-09T21:00:10.509308Z","entity":"article","guid":"2c41d6a3-b42d-4e41-b3d4-5c3464474df0","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you","modifiedDateTime":"2020-04-13T00:01:41.017768Z","project":"future","slug":"20200408-covid-19-can-boosting-your-immune-system-protect-you","cacheLastUpdated":1587442683497},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women","_id":"5e9820ae2567d5de2265988c","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fmartha-henriques"],"bodyIntro":"Covid-19 has profoundly different outcomes for men and women – and not just in terms of their health. For a virus that infects people indiscriminately, why does gender have such an effect?","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EFrom \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cbsnews.com\u002Flive-updates\u002Fcoronavirus-update-covid-19-latest-news-2020-04-02\u002F\"\u003Ebus drivers\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fuk-52208156\"\u003Eprime ministers\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, people from all walks of life are falling seriously ill with Covid-19. This has drawn remarks that the disease doesn&rsquo;t discriminate. The coronavirus is, after all, a more-or-less inanimate piece of floating genetic material. It is not capable of active discrimination.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnd yet the virus is having starkly different effects on different groups of people.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOne of the most pronounced divides to emerge regards gender. And how Covid-19 is affecting men and women differently isn&rsquo;t just in the way that the virus is making us sick &ndash; it&rsquo;s also in our long-term health and economic prospects.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisease differences\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOne of the most striking differences that has emerged so far is in the death rates of men and women.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn the US, for example, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nytimes.com\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F07\u002Fhealth\u002Fcoronavirus-new-york-men.html\"\u003Etwice as many men have been dying from the virus as women\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Similarly, \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.euro.who.int\u002Fen\u002Fhealth-topics\u002Fhealth-emergencies\u002Fcoronavirus-covid-19\u002Fweekly-surveillance-report\"\u003E69% of all coronavirus deaths across Western Europe\u003C\u002Fa\u003E have been male. Similar patterns have been seen in China and elsewhere.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOne team of researchers, led by Anna Purdie at University College London, is charting \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblogs.bmj.com\u002Fbmjgh\u002F2020\u002F03\u002F24\u002Fsex-gender-and-covid-19-disaggregated-data-and-health-disparities\u002F\"\u003Ethe gender differences in various countries\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and working to find out more about why.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor now, the reason is still unclear.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cul\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20180518-the-inequality-in-how-women-are-treated-for-pain\"\u003EPain bias: The health inequality rarely discussed\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20200330-coronavirus-are-children-immune-to-covid-19\"\u003EWhy children are not immune to Covid-19\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20190930-the-sexist-myths-about-gender-stereotypes-that-wont-die\"\u003EThe sexist myths that won&rsquo;t die\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOne theory is that women&rsquo;s immune response to the virus is stronger, says Philip Goulder, professor of immunology at the University of Oxford. &ldquo;The immune response throughout life to vaccines and infections is typically more aggressive and more effective in females compared to males,&rdquo; he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThis is partly down to the fact that women have two X chromosomes, whereas men have only one &ndash; which is important when it comes a coronavirus. &ldquo;In particular, the protein by which viruses such as coronavirus are sensed is encoded on the X chromosome,&rdquo; says Goulder. &ldquo;As a result, this protein is expressed at twice the dose on many immune cells in females compared to males, and the immune response to coronavirus is therefore amplified in females.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnother possibility is that the difference is down to gender-based lifestyle choices. &ldquo;There are important behavioural differences between the sexes, for example in smoking, which affect the level of pre-existing disease such as heart disease, chronic lung disease and cancer,&rdquo; says Goulder. &ldquo;These have a huge impact on the outcome from infections such as coronavirus.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The sex differential in smoking is especially marked in some countries such as China, where 50% of men smoke, compared to 5% in women.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"infographic","imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08940rh"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut at this stage of the pandemic, there&rsquo;s not enough evidence to say whether this is a result of biological differences, behavioural ones &ndash; or if there is an element of both at play.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFinancial fallout\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThere is, however, evidence emerging of another way that the virus is affecting men and women differently.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EMich&egrave;le Tertilt, an economist at Mannheim University in Germany, has been working with colleagues to compile evidence of how the pandemic has been affecting male versus female workers in the US. The lockdown already has resulted in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.dol.gov\u002Fsites\u002Fdolgov\u002Ffiles\u002FOPA\u002Fnewsreleases\u002Fui-claims\u002F20200510.pdf\"\u003Ewidespread job losses\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fbusiness-52000219\"\u003Emany economies are soon likely to face recession\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. \u003Cem\u003E(Read more about \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fworklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200327-unemployment-during-coronavirus-the-psychology-of-job-loss\"\u003Ethe psychology of job loss in the Covid-19 crisis\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.)\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut unemployment isn&rsquo;t falling equally across the board, which is in part due to the unique circumstances of this particular economic downturn. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s quite unusual and different from a typical recession,&rdquo; says Tertilt.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn the US, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bls.gov\u002Fnews.release\u002Fpdf\u002Fempsit.pdf\"\u003E1.4 million people become unemployed in March, the largest spike since 1975\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Women have been harder hit than men, with a 0.9% increase in unemployment compared to a 0.7% increase for men.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOne way that the current crisis is unusual is that, in a recession, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.spiegel.de\u002Finternational\u002Fgermany\u002Fa-very-male-recession-men-hit-hardest-by-job-losses-a-622373.html\"\u003Emen are often hit harder than women in terms of unemployment\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. This is because more men work in industries that are closely tied to economic cycles &ndash; such as construction and manufacturing. Women, conversely, dominate more in industries not tied to such cycles, such as healthcare and education.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut this time, other factors are having the largest impact on people&rsquo;s jobs.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOne is whether someone is a &ldquo;key&rdquo; or &ldquo;critical&rdquo; worker. Tertilt&rsquo;s team classed workers in healthcare, transportation, protective services (such as the police), farming, fishing and forestry, and maintenance and repair as &ldquo;critical workers&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBy this classification, 17% of employed women work in critical occupations, compared to 24% of all employed men.&nbsp; &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe second big factor is whether people are able to do their jobs remotely by telecommuting. Tertilt and her colleagues sorted jobs into whether they are possible to do by telecommuting or not &ndash; a business analyst might well be able to work remotely, but a bartender definitely can&rsquo;t.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETertilt found that more men had jobs that were telecommutable than women &ndash; at 28% for men versus 22% for women.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I was a little bit surprised at that,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;I was expecting more women to be in telecommutable jobs &ndash; for example, women in government jobs, office jobs and so forth.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;But once you start thinking about it, it makes perfect sense &ndash; a lot of women work in restaurants, in the travel industry. And worldwide, restaurants and bars are closed, and there is very limited travel.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p089415m"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EResearch carried out by the UK&rsquo;s Institute for Fiscal Studies paints a similar picture. It finds that UK women are about one-third more likely than men to work in a sector that has been heavily affected or entirely shut down due to the pandemic, such as the retail and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fbusiness-51923804\"\u003Ehospitality industries\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;From an economic perspective, low-paid, young, working-class women are known to be hit the hardest,&rdquo; says Natasha Mudhar, global chief executive and co-founder of The World We Want, an enterprise aimed at accelerating progress towards the UN&rsquo;s Sustainable Development Goals.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe gender pay gap compounds this inequality &ndash; not only are women losing jobs at higher rates, but they were making less money to begin with.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;For every pound that a man can spend on necessities during this crisis, a woman can only spend 82p,&rdquo; says Mudhar. In the US, the gender pay gap is similar, with \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.pewresearch.org\u002Ffact-tank\u002F2019\u002F03\u002F22\u002Fgender-pay-gap-facts\u002F\"\u003Ewomen earning 85% of what men earn\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. In \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.wgea.gov.au\u002Fdata\u002Ffact-sheets\u002Faustralias-gender-pay-gap-statistics\"\u003EAustralia it is 86%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, while in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwageindicator.org\u002Fdocuments\u002Fpublicationslist\u002Fpublications-2013\u002Fgender-pay-gap-in-formal-sector-in-india-2006-2013\"\u003EIndia it is 75%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. And this is worse for women of some races and ethnicities than others &ndash; in the US, for example, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fiwpr.org\u002Fpublications\u002Fgender-wage-gap-2017\u002F\"\u003Eblack women earn 21% less than white women\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESingle parents have been hit even harder. Tertilt&rsquo;s research estimates that there are 20 million single parents in the US, three-quarters of whom are women. &ldquo;Think about it &ndash; they won&rsquo;t be able to work,&rdquo; says Tertilt. &ldquo;Even if they&rsquo;re a nurse or a doctor, even if they have a job within critical infrastructure &ndash; they might have kids at home and they can&rsquo;t leave them alone.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEven for single parents in theoretically telecommutable jobs, it may not be realistic to continue to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fworklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200401-how-to-work-from-home-with-your-kids-during-coronavirus\"\u003Ework with small children who require constant attention\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. &ldquo;Especially for single mums, there is no other margin,&rdquo; says Tertilt. &ldquo;They cannot hire a nanny or ask a neighbour or a grandmother. They are, by and large, losing their jobs.&rdquo;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnother problem is that in countries that have a government-backed furlough scheme (including the UK, Germany and the US), these parents might not be eligible if they quit their job before they could be furloughed. What&rsquo;s more, they may not be eligible for unemployment benefits if they give up their jobs.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08941nq"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Even if workers quit voluntarily because of childcare, they should be eligible,&rdquo; says Tertilt. &ldquo;The requirement that people should be &lsquo;seeking work&rsquo; should be removed temporarily, until schools and day care re-open. It makes no sense in the current situation.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExposing inequality\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThis makes Covid-19 the latest in a long line of epidemics that have brought economic inequalities to the fore, including those around gender.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;All epidemics have gendered effects,&rdquo; says Clare Wenham, an associate professor of global health policy at the London School of Economics and Political Science. &ldquo;The problem that is no one had talked about it, and policymakers weren&rsquo;t aware.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWenham and her colleagues researched the impacts of the Zika and Ebola outbreaks on men and women, and are now looking at Covid-19.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOne consequence of the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F28588954\"\u003EEbola epidemic in Sierra Leone was a dramatic increase in maternal mortality\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The World Health Organization has emphasised that maternity health services remain essential during the pandemic, and that all women &ldquo;have the right to high quality care before, during and after childbirth&rdquo;. But that is not always put into practice.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We know from previous outbreaks, everything [in terms of resources] goes to the outbreak,&rdquo; says Wenham. &ldquo;That means routine service provision is disrupted. And the first thing to go is maternal health services.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOther women&rsquo;s health services, such as access to contraception, are also precarious unless governments state that they are essential services. The family planning organisation Marie Stopes has estimated that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.mariestopes.org\u002Fcovid-19\"\u003E9.5 million women&nbsp;and girls worldwide could risk losing access to Marie Stopes contraception and abortion services in 2020 because of the pandemic\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EReports of domestic violence, too, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fuk-wales-52076789\"\u003Ehave surged as a result of the pandemic\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. In France, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.france24.com\u002Fen\u002F20200406-un-chief-decries-horrifying-rise-in-domestic-violence-amid-virus-lockdown\"\u003Ecases rose by a third in the first week of lockdown\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, while \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpursuit.unimelb.edu.au\u002Farticles\u002Fdomestic-violence-isolation-and-covid-19\"\u003Ereports are up 75% in Australia\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and cases have \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fnews.un.org\u002Fen\u002Fstory\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F1061132\"\u003Edoubled in Lebanon\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. While domestic violence can affect men or women, women experience a disproportionate amount; in the US, they are \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncadv.org\u002Fstatistics\"\u003Etwice as likely to experience violence from an intimate partner\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and 14 times as likely to be raped, for example.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We know domestic violence normally happens in the home,&rdquo; says Wenham. &ldquo;Then you shut people you in the home in a stressful period when people don&rsquo;t have money and can&rsquo;t go to work. You don&rsquo;t have to be a rocket scientist to see why that results in more domestic violence.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Chr align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" \u002F\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p089424h"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe picture is undeniably bleak at present &ndash; and for both genders in different ways.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor men, particularly those in older age groups, the immediate risk of death from the disease is the greatest concern. For women, who are more likely to recover from the virus, other repercussions of Covid-19 may last for years to come.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnd it is not too late for governments to respond to those hit hardest economically, says Wenham. There is plenty that could be done now to ensure those hit hardest economically are able to recover: &ldquo;We should be making sure there is economic stimulus for women during and post the outbreak to get them back into work,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;Is there childcare provision when women are trying to do so?&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnd, through the gloom, Tertilt&rsquo;s research has unearthed two silver linings for gender equality.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe first is workplace flexibility. &ldquo;Millions of businesses are adjusting to working-from-home schemes on the fly right now,&rdquo; Tertilt says. In some parts of the US, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcorporate.comcast.com\u002Fcovid-19\u002Fnetwork\"\u003EMarch saw more than a 200% increase in teleconferencing compared with the previous month\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. &ldquo;There is some scope that this will be shifting norms to some extent, and that will make it easier to combine careers and families,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;Women are going to benefit more from these changes in business culture and workplace flexibility because historically they are the main providers of childcare.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe second upshot affects a small but significant slice of the workforce. Tertilt&rsquo;s study looked at heterosexual couples, 8-12% of whom may be thrown into reverse gender roles by lockdown, she says. &ldquo;Think of a couple where she is a medical doctor on the front lines, and the husband has an office job that is possible to do by telecommuting,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;In such a couple, it is very likely that he will suddenly be the main childcare provider. She is at the hospital and he is at home telecommuting and somehow watching the kids.&rdquo; Given that in the US 60% of childcare is provided by women, Tertilt finds, this could lead to a sizeable shift.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThese changes in care can lead to lasting effects down the road. Policies in countries such as Germany and Sweden have found that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC6124678\u002F\"\u003Eintroducing paternity leave increases the level of involvement of fathers in their children&rsquo;s care for years afterward\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Based on that, I would infer that even here, if lockdown lasts only a month or two, I think there will be long-term effects,&rdquo; says Tertilt. &ldquo;If it lasts longer, the effects might be larger.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08942fb"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EA health crisis like coronavirus emphasises and exacerbates inequalities of all kinds, and gender is only one of them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;All this intersects with other areas of inequality,&rdquo; says Wenham.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn the US, for example, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-us-canada-52194018\"\u003Ecities with large African American communities have borne the brunt of the epidemic\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. But this underscores an issue that existed before the new coronavirus. Structural inequalities around race are \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fbooks\u002FNBK425844\u002F\"\u003Estrongly linked to profound health disparities\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Black residents of Chicago typically live nearly nine years less than their white neighbours, for example, according to Chicago public health commissioner Allison Arwady. \u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnd as the evidence on Covid-19 has overwhelmingly shown so far, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.co.uk\u002Fnews\u002Fhealth-51703892\"\u003Ethose who have underlying health conditions are more likely to die with the virus\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. And in the US, underlying conditions like \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.minorityhealth.hhs.gov\u002Fomh\u002Fbrowse.aspx?lvl=4&amp;lvlid=18\"\u003Ediabetes\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.minorityhealth.hhs.gov\u002Fomh\u002Fbrowse.aspx?lvl=4&amp;lvlid=19\"\u003Eheart disease\u003C\u002Fa\u003E disproportionately affect African Americans.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We know gender and race and religion and disability all intersect in other areas of health,&rdquo; says Wenham. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s no reason to think it won&rsquo;t be the same here.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhile the virus doesn&rsquo;t discriminate, that doesn&rsquo;t mean that all parts of society are equally at risk.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIf anything, it is quite the opposite &ndash; this virus is throwing health inequalities across the board into sharper relief than ever.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAs an award-winning science site, BBC Future is committed to bringing you evidence-based analysis and myth-busting stories around the new coronavirus. You can read more of our&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Ftags\