tly","image":["p089431v"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e9821532567d5de226b3500"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fgender"],"summaryLong":"Covid-19 has profoundly different outcomes for men and women – and not just in terms of their health.","summaryShort":"Covid-19 has profoundly different outcomes for men and women","tag":["tag\u002Fcovid-19"],"creationDateTime":"2020-04-13T00:00:40.883955Z","entity":"article","guid":"f430f002-3032-4828-a75a-3d117354a6ae","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women","modifiedDateTime":"2020-04-13T00:01:41.017768Z","project":"future","slug":"20200409-why-covid-19-is-different-for-men-and-women","cacheLastUpdated":1587442683498},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work","_id":"5e9d64dc2567d5de2238efad","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fjessica-brown"],"bodyIntro":"From orange juice to zinc lozenges, chicken soup to garlic capsules, there are plenty of home remedies for the common cold. But is there any evidence that they work?","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAs many countries urge populations to stay at home, many of us are paying more attention to our diets and how the food we eat can support our health. To help sort out the fact from the fiction, BBC Future is updating some of our most popular \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Ftags\u002Fnutrition\"\u003Enutrition\u003C\u002Fa\u003E stories from our archive.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EOur colleagues at \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbcgoodfood.com\u002Ffeature\u002Fstay-home-get-cooking\"\u003EBBC Good Food\u003C\u002Fa\u003E are focusing on practical solutions for ingredient swaps, nutritious storecupboard recipes and all aspects of cooking and eating during lockdown.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThere are few experiences as universal as catching a cold. And while there are around 200 viruses that cause it, there seem to be almost as many home remedies to combat it.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut do any of them work?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAt the core of any home remedy is the idea that it bolsters our immune system. When a virus enters our bodies, it comes up against two systems of defence: the innate immune system tries to flush invading cells out, while the adaptive system targets specific pathogens that the body already has had contact with and creates memory cells of new ones, so the body can fight them off if they return. This is why we tend to get chicken pox only once, whereas the common cold &ndash; which changes its appearance as it passes from one person to the next, confusing our memory cells &ndash; is something we can experience dozens of times.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20161208-why-vitamin-supplements-could-kill-you\"\u003EWhy vitamin pills may be bad for you\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20181010-do-vitamin-d-supplements-work\"\u003EShould everyone be taking vitamin D?\u003C\u002Fa\u003E \u003Cbr \u002F\u003E&bull; \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20141212-dos-and-donts-for-common-colds\"\u003EDo&rsquo;s and don&rsquo;ts for common colds\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s well-known that both lifestyle habits and diet affect the strength of our immune systems.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06tk635"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut because the immune system is only impaired in otherwise healthy people when we have a vitamin or mineral deficiency, supplementing our diets with so-called cold-busting foods will make little difference if we already have a relatively good diet, says Charles Bangham, head of the Division of Infectious Diseases at Imperial College London.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Only if you&rsquo;re short of a vital nutrient, such as vitamin, zinc or iron, will supplementing that particular item be very helpful. But if you eat a balanced diet, adding more of these things doesn&rsquo;t make the immune system any more efficient,&rdquo; he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIt should also be pointed out that many of the same remedies we're told can cure the common cold are also being circulated on social media with the promise that they can keep us safe during the current virus pandemic.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupplement solution\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EStudies looking into cures for the common cold have found that they can make a difference.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe vast majority of these studies concentrate on supplements, rather than food &ndash; in fact, no reliable research has been done on whether a popular cure like chicken soup actually makes a difference.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut one supplement that may help is popular home remedy garlic. In one small study, 146 healthy adults were \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F11697022?ordinalpos=1&amp;itool=EntrezSystem2.PEntrez.Pubmed.Pubmed_ResultsPanel.Pubmed_DefaultReportPanel.Pubmed_RVDocSum\"\u003Egiven either a placebo or a daily garlic supplement\u003C\u002Fa\u003E for 12 weeks over winter. The placebo group contracted 65 colds, resulting in 366 days of sickness &ndash; whereas those who had garlic supplements only contracted 24 colds, with 111 days of sickness between them.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06tk66w"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"One review on vitamin C supplements didn&rsquo;t find that supplements greatly reduce the risk of getting colds","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAnother supplement many people reach for when they feel cold symptoms is vitamin C. Some research suggests it too can help &ndash; though not as much as you might think. One review analysing 29 studies on vitamin C supplements didn&rsquo;t find that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cochranelibrary.com\u002Fcdsr\u002Fdoi\u002F10.1002\u002F14651858.CD000980.pub4\u002Fepdf\u002Ffull\"\u003Esupplements greatly reduce the risk of getting colds\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, or that they alleviate symptoms. But it did find that children saw a 14% reduction in the length of their colds; in adults, the reduction was 8%. Researchers concluded that since the supplements are low-risk, it may be worthwhile trying them to see if they can help.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOrange juice may be less useful: there is no robust evidence that orange juice helps prevent colds, alleviate symptoms or reduce a cold&rsquo;s length. This is because it doesn&rsquo;t contain high enough doses of vitamin C to have the same impact as daily supplements, says Harri Hemil&auml;, a public health researcher at the University of Helsinki and author of the vitamin C supplements review. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fndb.nal.usda.gov\u002Fndb\u002Fsearch\u002Flist?SYNCHRONIZER_TOKEN=1ff4c234-ad63-47cc-9c10-d0eb4253ec43&amp;SYNCHRNIZER_URI=%2Fndb%2Fsearch%2Flist&amp;qt=&amp;qlookup=orange+juice&amp;ds=&amp;manu=\"\u003EA standard small bottle of fresh orange juice\u003C\u002Fa\u003E has around 72mg of vitamin C, according to the US Department of Agriculture &ndash; that&rsquo;s more than the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nhs.uk\u002Fconditions\u002Fvitamins-and-minerals\u002Fvitamin-c\u002F\"\u003Erecommended daily minimum\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of 40mg, but still less than many supplements.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06tk6c3"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThen there&rsquo;s zinc. One review examining the effectiveness of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC4359576\u002F\"\u003Edaily zinc acetate lozenges on the common cold\u003C\u002Fa\u003E found that they shortened the duration of runny and blocked noses by around a third, plus led to 22% less sneezing and almost half as much coughing.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe study concluded that if started within 24 hours of the first symptoms, 80mg daily zinc acetate lozenges may help treat the common cold.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Patients with a cold who were given zinc lozenges recovered three times faster","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EHowever, Hemil&auml; argues it&rsquo;s more accurate to study recovering from a cold fully, rather than measuring symptom duration &ndash; which avoids data being affected by people dropping out of the study before fully recovering from their cold, and to avoid those with extended colds skewing the findings. His study of 199 common cold patients found that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC5410113\u002F\"\u003Ethose with a cold who were given zinc lozenges\u003C\u002Fa\u003E recovered three times faster.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOften, scientists say that vitamins and minerals are best consumed through foods, rather than supplements &ndash; though they point out that, as with vitamin C, it&rsquo;s often easier to get high doses of a vitamin through supplements.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06tk6j2"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EFor zinc, however, the opposite is true. In order to be effective against colds, zinc must come from lozenges and not from ordinary zinc tablets or zinc-rich foods, Hemil&auml; says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Zinc lozenges are slowly dissolved in the throat region and the effect of zinc is local,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;We don&rsquo;t know what the biochemical mechanism of this effect is. But studies finding zinc lozenges to be effective used large lozenges that have dissolved for up to 30 minutes in the mouth.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECold comfort\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStill, one complication is that researchers haven&rsquo;t tended to look at whether people were deficient in something like vitamin C or zinc before they started a regimen. So, any cold-fighting benefit might be down to the fact that by taking a supplement, some participants were correcting a deficiency, rather than the supplement making a difference for already healthy people.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06tk6mm"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAnother complication is the power of placebo. Of course, many studies, like that on garlic supplements, do control with a placebo-only group &ndash; so the effect for those isn&rsquo;t down to placebo alone.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut if we swear that something for which there&rsquo;s limited or no scientific evidence, like chicken soup or orange juice, really cures us, it may be down to placebo. Placebos have been found to be effective in alleviating many symptoms, from \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nature.com\u002Farticles\u002Fs41467-018-05859-1\"\u003Epain\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjournals.plos.org\u002Fplosone\u002Farticle?id=10.1371\u002Fjournal.pone.0015591\"\u003Eirritable bowel syndrome\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, although the reasons why aren&rsquo;t yet fully understood. And whether for vitamin C or chicken soup, the placebo effect alone could help us get over a cold.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"People who believed in the alleged cold-fighting properties of echinacea experienced milder and shorter colds when taking daily doses, compared to than those who didn&rsquo;t believe in it","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOne study found that people who believed in the alleged \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3133578\u002F\"\u003Ecold-fighting properties of herbal remedy\u003C\u002Fa\u003E echinacea experienced milder and shorter colds when taking daily doses, compared to than those who didn&rsquo;t believe in it. Previous studies in which participants weren't aware they were getting \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpmc\u002Farticles\u002FPMC3056276\u002F\"\u003Eechinacea weren't shown to improve cold symptoms\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt works the other way, too. Milk has long been thought to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F16373954\"\u003Eworsen mucus production when we have a cold,\u003C\u002Fa\u003E although this has now been debunked. But one study found that people who believed that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\u002Fpubmed\u002F16373954\"\u003Emilk causes mucus\u003C\u002Fa\u003E reported more respiratory symptoms after drinking it. (\u003Cem\u003EFind out more in our BBC Future story \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20170421-should-you-avoid-ice-cream-when-you-have-a-cold\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003EShould you avoid dairy when you have a cold?\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E).\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile placebos are usually administered by doctors in clinical trials, the placebo power of home remedies can come from our everyday lives, says Felicity&nbsp;Bishop, associate professor of health psychology at the University of Southampton.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Studies show the power of the placebo pill comes from a trusted relationship between patients and healthcare professionals, someone who is caring and can offer treatments with confidence,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;And this is kind of what parents do when we&rsquo;re young. It&rsquo;s the nature of the relationship is important, rather than who that person is.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p06tk6q6"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-16"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs well as trusted friends and family, the placebo effect could also be strengthened by how foods are marketed, Bishop adds.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe good news? Knowing that home remedies are placebos won&rsquo;t necessarily stop them from alleviating our symptoms. &ldquo;Open-label placebos, when a doctor tells the patient something is a placebo but that it&rsquo;s helped some people, can still make patients better,&rdquo; she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother effect could be the comfort induced by such foods. Dietician Sarah Schenker says the comfort of having chicken soup, for example, could help someone with a cold to feel slightly better.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERather than how much vitamin C we stock up on, the chances of being able to stave off bugs in winter depends largely on the individual &ndash; including how much we believe in placebos, but also because of our genes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-17"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Some people&rsquo;s genes make them particularly susceptible to certain diseases &ndash; Sarah Schenker","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20181203-do-cold-remedies-like-chicken-soup-and-vitamin-c-really-work-18"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Some people&rsquo;s genes make them particularly susceptible to certain diseases. It&rsquo;s much more important to realise we all differ genetically from one another &ndash; when some people have the flu, they don&rsquo;t realise they&rsquo;ve got it, while others get a very serious disease. This is partly determined by your genes, which have much more of an impact.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor the majority of us with healthy immune systems, we can do little more than rely on the power of placebos to get over winter bugs&hellip; though popping some zinc or garlic supplements might help too.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003